    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "386c6da2_2b4e6481",
        "filename": "experimental/canvaskit/skottie_bindings.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 5641
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-27T22:41:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not 100% sure this is safe: MultiFrameImageAsset wraps an SkCodec built from this SkData, and I\u0027m pretty sure our codecs decode on demand - so they must keep a reference to the original data (maybe scroggo can confirm).\n\nIf that\u0027s the case, the animation object will have live references to these arrays.  When are they deleted - are there any guarantees that their lifespan \u003e animation lifespan?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 219,
        "startChar": 42,
        "endLine": 219,
        "endChar": 57
      },
      "revId": "cee90a083ef458d9e89a80ea2ab1e25575f3321b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8120d351_f346aa25",
        "filename": "experimental/canvaskit/skottie_bindings.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-02-28T14:21:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The idea was they\u0027d be allocated in JS land and then the C++ side would assume control and be responsible for deleting that memory when it closes. I had assumed since addImage does a std::move() that it would take ownership of the SkData and cleanup.\n\nYou did remind me of some arrays that I do need to cleanup in JS land (for passing the strings, etc)\n\nI changed this to MakeFromMalloc() with the hopes that the C++ will properly own this (and free it on destructor);",
      "parentUuid": "386c6da2_2b4e6481",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 219,
        "startChar": 42,
        "endLine": 219,
        "endChar": 57
      },
      "revId": "cee90a083ef458d9e89a80ea2ab1e25575f3321b",
